  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_23485243" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/23485243" />
    <a title="George" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/232918-george"><img alt="George" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1364883129p2/232918.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/23485243?book_show_action=true">Jun 01, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="George" class="user" itemprop="url" name="George" href="/user/show/232918-george">George</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer23485243" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13255597215984979303"> I was initially afraid that these characters would sound the same as the ones in the Rainbow Boys series, but luckily I was wrong. The story still had a unique voice, despite covering familiar ground: coming out, high school, and family issues. The major issue that this book tackles in a pretty great way is homosexuality and the bible. Tough topic, right? I know!<br/> I wish I was much more familiar with the bible so I could form my own opinions on what the big book has to say on the issues the char</span>
  <span id="freeText13255597215984979303" style="display:none"> I was initially afraid that these characters would sound the same as the ones in the Rainbow Boys series, but luckily I was wrong. The story still had a unique voice, despite covering familiar ground: coming out, high school, and family issues. The major issue that this book tackles in a pretty great way is homosexuality and the bible. Tough topic, right? I know!<br /> I wish I was much more familiar with the bible so I could form my own opinions on what the big book has to say on the issues the characters discuss, but it wasn't necessary to follow the story. Wow, that sentence was too long. What I found really stupendous(or maybe even, tremendous? Eh, why not?) was how the characters presented the bible excerpts. First, they discussed how those excerpts were traditionally interpreted and then one of the main characters would refute their ideas by giving them a new perspective that made more sense. <br /> Overall, the characters were likeable and the story has a good pace. Sanchez is always good at portraying inner(does a hyphen belong here?) turmoil that makes it really easy to sympathize and become invested in the characters. </span>
  <a data-text-id="13255597215984979303" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


